
DETERMINISTIC CHAOS IN AN X-RAY PULSAR?

Hercules X-1 is an X-ray pulsar.  Every 1.4 seconds it emits a pulse
of X-rays towards the Earth.  The source is an X-ray binary, with a
1.7 day binary period.  Material is accreting from a companion star
onto a compact neutron star with a very strong magnetic field.  The
material, which is ionized plasma, is funnel by the magnetic field
onto the neutron star's magnetic poles.  There it forms a shock at
the neutron star surface and X-rays are emitted.  As the neutron star
rotates, the beams of X-rays sweep past the Earth, like a lighthouse,
giving rise to a pulsed light curve.

The search for astrophysical sources showing evidence for deterministic
chaos is almost a decade old (see review by Scargle 1992).
Voges, Atmanspacher, and Scheingraber (1987) have analyzed data from
Her X-1 and concluded that it exhibits a fractal dimension of
approximately 2.3.  They used the method of phase space reconstruction
and dimensional extraction of Grassberger and Procaccia (1983) to derive
this result.  Norris and Matilsky (1989) showed that there is no evidence
for a strange attractor in Her X-1; rather there is an ordinary attractor
which is contaminated by noise.  The resultant smearing of points in the
reconstructed phase space necessarily leads to spurious measurements
of dimensionality.
